The Broadcasting Act 1990 is a good example of regulation and prohibits the broadcasting of:

• any programme which offends good taste or decency;
• material which incites crime or disorder;
• matter which is offensive to public feeling;
• news which is not impartial and accurate;
• religious programmes which are not responsible; and
• any illegal content, such as obscene or racially inflammatory material

Independent regulation is important. Self-regulation clearly does not work.

Extract from www.organdonation.nhs.uk dated 15th January 2016;
"More than 500 families in the UK have said no to organ donation taking place since 1 April 2010, despite knowing or being informed their relative was on the NHS Organ Donor Register and wanted to donate. These family refusals have resulted in an estimated 1200 people missing out on a potentially life-saving transplant."

I think the above says it all. People are registering as they want to help but then next of kin refuse.
